Note: availability of a charset depends on whether the corresponding
Windows code page is installed on the system.


Layout Files (.lay)
-------------------
Each document type (default, html, program, ...) has a .lay file in
the type/ subfolder next to GreenPad.exe.  You can edit these files
with any text editor, or use Settings > Edit Layout in GreenPad.

The file is UTF-16 LE with BOM.  Each line has the form "key=value".

Colors (6-digit hex RGB, e.g. FF0000 = red):
  ct=RRGGBB   Text color
  ck=RRGGBB   Keyword color
  cb=RRGGBB   Background color
  cr=RRGGBB   Read-only background color
  cc=RRGGBB   Comment color
  cn=RRGGBB   Special / control character color
  cl=RRGGBB   Line number color

Font:
  ft=name     Font face name (e.g. Consolas)
  sz=N        Font size in points (e.g. 10)
  fw=N        Font weight  0=don't care  400=normal  700=bold
  ff=N        Font style flags: 1=italic  2=underline  4=strikeout
              (combine with |: e.g. 3 = italic+underline)
  fx=N        Font width in points (0 = use default width)
  cs=N        Font charset (Windows LOGFONT lfCharSet value)
  fq=N        Font quality (Windows LOGFONT lfQuality value)

Tab / Special Characters:
  tb=N        Tab width in characters (e.g. 4)
  sc=BBBBB    Show special characters: five 0/1 flags for
              [EOF marker, line endings, tabs, half-width spaces,
               full-width spaces / control chars]
              Example: sc=11101  (show all except half-width spaces)

Wrapping:
  wp=N        Wrap type: -1=none  0=at window right edge  1=at ww chars
  ww=N        Wrap width in characters (used when wp=1)
  ws=N        Smart wrap: 1=wrap at word boundaries  0=wrap at character

Line numbers:
  ln=N        Show line numbers: 1=yes  0=no


Syntax Highlighting (.kwd)
--------------------------
Place .kwd files in the type/ subdirectory.  GreenPad matches the
current filename against the patterns listed in Settings to select
the active document type and its associated .kwd file.

Format (line by line):
  Line 1: four flags (0 or 1) — CaseSensitive EnSingleQuote EnDoubleQuote EnEscape
           Recommended: 0111 (case-insensitive, string-aware)
                     or 1111 (case-sensitive, string-aware)
  Line 2: block-comment start symbol (e.g.  /*  )
  Line 3: block-comment end symbol   (e.g.  */  )
  Line 4: line-comment start symbol  (e.g.  //  )
  Line 5+: keywords, one per line

Example header for C/C++:
  1111
  /*
  */
  //
  auto
  bool
  break
  ...

The default comment character for plain text files is '>'.
Alt+Q (Quote) prepends this character; Alt+N (Unquote) removes it.


Regular Expressions
-------------------
GreenPad supports two regex engines selected automatically at startup:

  * PCRE2 (full Perl-compatible regex) — used when pcre2-16.dll is
    present in the same directory as GreenPad.exe.
    Supports: groups, back-references, lookahead/behind, Unicode
    properties, etc.  Full PCRE2 syntax applies.

    Replacement strings support back-references:
      \0  entire match
      \1 … \9  captured groups 1–9

  * Built-in NFA engine (fallback when pcre2-16.dll is absent):

    Quantifiers:    ?  *  +
    Alternation:    a|b
    Grouping:       ( ... )
    Anchors:        ^  start of line    $  end of line
    Escape:         \t  tab    \\  backslash    \[  literal [
    Character classes:
      [abc]    matches a, b, or c
      [^abc]   matches any character except a, b, c
      [a-z]    range
      \w  \W   [0-9a-zA-Z_] and its complement
      \d  \D   [0-9] and its complement
      \s  \S   [ \t] and its complement

    Limitations of the built-in engine:
      * Searches line by line (cannot match across newlines)
      * No back-references
      * Greedy only (no lazy quantifiers)

Both engines perform case-insensitive matching when the "Ignore case"
option is checked in the Find dialog.

Insert Unicode code point (Ctrl+I):
  Type a code point value and press Enter.  Prefixes:
    (none) or x   hexadecimal   e.g.  1F600  or  x1F600
    . (dot)       decimal       e.g.  .128512
    o or O        octal         e.g.  o370300


External Programs
-----------------
Configure external programs in Settings (View > Settings).

  GrepExe   Path and arguments for the external grep tool.
            Placeholders:
              %D   current directory
              %F   full path of current file
              %N   filename only (no path)
              %S   current selection text

            Example:
              C:\Tools\grep.exe -n "%S" "%F"

  HelpExe   Path and arguments for the F1 context help tool.
            Same %D/%F/%N/%S placeholders apply.

  ExFilter  Path and arguments for the external filter (Ctrl+\).
            The selected text is piped to stdin; stdout replaces
            the selection.


Settings (GreenPad.ini)
-----------------------
The ini file lives next to GreenPad.exe (or in %APPDATA%\GreenPad
when shared-config mode is disabled).

Useful manual settings:

  [GreenPad]
  Language=ja-JP       Force UI language (overrides OS display language).
                       Available: en-US  ja-JP  ko-KR  zh-CN  zh-TW  ru-RU
  WarnOnModified=0     Disable "file changed outside GreenPad" warning.
  HelpExe=...          External help program (see above).
  GrepExe=...          External grep program.
  NewfileCharset=65001 Default encoding for new files (UTF-8 with BOM).

  [SharedConfig]
  Enable=1             Use a single ini shared by all user accounts on
                       this machine (useful for portable installations).

Q: How to change the default font for all document types?
A: Use View > Font to choose a font interactively.  GreenPad saves it
   as the fallback font in the ini file.  Individual document types
   can override this in their .lay files.

Q: How to open or save a file whose encoding is not in the dropdown?
A: Type the Windows code page number directly into the encoding combo
   box in the Open / Save / ReOpen dialog.
   Use the special negative codes (see "Character Encodings") for
   non-Windows encodings (UTF-1, EUC-JP, etc.).

Q: How to share settings across users on the same machine?
A: Add the following to GreenPad.ini:
     [SharedConfig]
     Enable=1


